default3default. The process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors default3
default.1 
defaultOur second concern relates 
defaultto the
default process for approving, compelling and establishing academies and free schools, including working with sponsors
default. The current process is undemocratic, dismissive of other stakeholder views and a centrally co
defaultntrolled – rather than locally-
defaultcontrolled pr
defaultocess.
default3
default.2 
defaultT
defaulthe Secretary of State
default is riding roughshod over the views of 
defaultlocal 
defaultstakeholders rather than seeking to ‘win’ an educational argument by engaging in genuine consultation and democratic decision making. There is a presumption that academy conversi
defaulton is always the best solution. The 
defaultmanner in which unaccountable brokers pressurise governors to ‘opt for’ academy status has been described to us as like having a ‘gun put to your head’. 
defaultIn these cases, ‘forced’ academy conversion becomes ‘voluntary’. As
default the process lacks both genuine accountability and any transparency, parents are often suspicious of the conversion process.
default3
default.3 
defaultAcademy conversion can actually be a distraction
default for school improvement
default. 
defaultThe time and effort of meeting brokers and potential s
defaultponsors can ta
defaultke the school leadership away from
default the vital task of improving teaching 
defaultand 
defaultlearning. 
default3
default.4 
defaultThere are also concerns about the way Interim Executive Boards (IEBs) are used. It seems that they are sometimes populated with employees/representativ
defaultes of the proposed sponsors. We believe this creates potential conflicts of interest over the decision to convert.
default Similarly there 
defaultis 
defaultconcern
default that academy chains are cherry picking certain 
defaultschools 
defaultfor ‘takeover
default’. Sometimes i
defaultt appears 
defaultthat 
defaultit is not always 
defaultthe schools that are most in need of improvement but schools that are already improving
default that become academies
default. 
default Whilst sponsor can choose whether to take over a school – schools cannot choose whether or not to be taken over. 
default3
default.5 
defaultFinally there are concerns about the experience, viability and accountability of academy chains. There a huge numbers of new chains. Often these are single individual head teachers who ‘morph’ into chains by taking over a couple of local school. They becom
defaulte executive heads and some label themselves CEOs. Their focus becomes building the business. In other cases foreign venture capital lies behind
default head teachers, former council and government education officers. They combine to create companies that have very
default little public face and seemingly no accountability to local people or OFSTED.
